      " `longestIncreasingSubsequence` satisfies the specified `longestIncreasingSubsequence_postcond`. \n\nFirst, let's understand what the problem is asking:\n\n- We have a list of integers `nums`.\n- We have a pre-condition `h_precond` which is `True` (as per the definition of `longestIncreasingSubsequence_precond`).\n- We have a function `longestIncreasingSubsequence` that computes the length of the longest increasing subsequence (LIS) in `nums`.\n- We have a post-condition `longestIncreasingSubsequence_postcond` which states that the computed result is indeed the maximum possible length of an increasing subsequence in `nums`.\n\nThe theorem `longestIncreasingSubsequence_spec_satisfied` states that for any list `nums` and pre-condition `h_precond`, the result of `longestIncreasingSubsequence` applied to `nums` and `h_precond` satisfies the post-condition `longestIncreasingSubsequence_postcond`.\n\nThe definition of `longestIncreasingSubsequence` uses a recursive approach with memoization (via `let` bindings) to compute the length of the LIS. It defines:\n1. A helper function `helper` that computes the length of the LIS ending at a given index with a given previous element.\n2. A `max2` function to return the maximum of two natural numbers.\n3. A `listLength` function to compute the length of a list.\n\nThe definition of `longestIncreasingSubsequence_postcond` is:\n```tactics\nlet allSubseq := (nums.foldl fun acc x => acc ++ acc.map (fun sub => x :: sub)) [[]] |>.map List.reverse\nlet increasingSubseqLens := allSubseq.filter (fun l => List.Pairwise (· < ·) l) |>.map (·.length)\nincreasingSubseqLens.contains result ∧ increasingSubseqLens.all (· ≤ result)\n```\nThis states that the result is in the set of all lengths of increasing subsequences (`increasingSubseqLens`), and it's the maximum element of this set.\n\nTo prove the theorem, we need to show that the result computed by `longestIncreasingSubsequence` is indeed the maximum length of an increasing subsequence in `nums`.\n\nThe proof strategy is likely to involve:\n1. Showing that the result computed by the function is indeed an increasing subsequence.\n2. Showing that it's the longest such subsequence.\n\nLet's think about how to approach this proof.\n\nFirst, we need to understand what the function `longestIncreasingSubsequence` is computing. The helper function `helper` computes the length of the longest increasing subsequence ending at the `h` element (with `h` being the head of the current list segment `t`). The function `helper` uses recursion to compute this.\n\nTo prove the theorem, we need to:\n1. Show that the result is in the set `increasingSubseqLens`.\n2. Show that it's the maximum element of this set.\n\nLet's think about how to show it's in the set. We need to show that the result is the length of some increasing subsequence. The function `longestIncreasingSubsequence` computes the length of the longest increasing subsequence, so the result itself is the length of the longest increasing subsequence. Therefore, the result should be in the set `increasingSubseqLens`.\n\nTo show it's the maximum, we need to show that for any other increasing subsequence, its length is less than or equal to the result.\n\nThe definition of `allSubseq` is `(nums.foldl fun acc x => acc ++ acc.map (fun sub => x :: sub)) [[]] |>.map List.reverse`. This is generating all possible subsequnces of `nums` by repeatedly adding elements to the front of the existing subsequnces. Then `allSubseq` is the set of all possible subsequnces.\n\nThen `increasingSubseqLens` is filtering this set to only include strictly increasing subsequences and mapping them to their lengths.\n\nThe result of `longestIncreasingSubsequence` is the length of the longest such subsequence.\n\nTo prove the theorem, we need to show that the computed result is in the set `increasingSubseqLens` and is the maximum element of this set.\n\nLet's think about how to show this in Lean. We need to:\n1. Show that the result is the length of some increasing subsequence.\n2. Show that it's the maximum such length.\n\nFor the first part, we can construct the longest increasing subsequence and show that its length equals the computed result. For the second part, we need to show that any other increasing subsequence has length less than or equal to the computed result.\n\nThis is a standard proof structure for showing that a computed result is the maximum of a set.\n\nLet's proceed to write the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Data.List.Basic\n-- !benchmark @end import\n\n-- !benchmark @start solution_aux\n\n-- !benchmark @end solution_aux\n\n-- !benchmark @start precond_aux\n\n-- !benchmark @end precond_aux\n@[reducible, simp]\ndef longestIncreasingSubsequence_precond (nums : List Int) : Prop :=\n  -- !benchmark @start precond\n  True\n  -- !benchmark @end precond\n\n\n-- !benchmark @start code_aux\n\n-- !benchmark @end code_aux\n\n\ndef longestIncreasingSubsequence (nums : List Int) (h_precond : longestIncreasingSubsequence_precond (nums)) : Nat :=\n  -- !benchmark @start code\n  let max2 (a : Nat) (b : Nat) : Nat :=\n    if a > b then a else b\n\n  let rec listLength (l : List Int) : Nat :=\n    match l with\n    | []      => 0\n    | _ :: xs => 1 + listLength xs\n\n  let rec helper (lst : List Int) (prev : Option Int) : Nat :=\n    match lst with\n    | [] => 0\n    | h :: t =>\n        let canTake : Bool :=\n          if prev = none then true\n          else if prev.get! < h then true else false\n        let withTake : Nat :=\n          if canTake then 1 + helper t (some h) else 0\n        let withoutTake : Nat := helper t prev\n        max2 withTake withoutTake\n\n  let result := helper nums none\n  result\n  -- !benchmark @end code\n\n\n-- !benchmark @start postcond_aux\n\n-- !benchmark @end postcond_aux\n\n\n@[reducible, simp]\ndef longestIncreasingSubsequence_postcond (nums : List Int) (result: Nat) (h_precond : longestIncreasingSubsequence_precond (nums)) : Prop :=\n  -- !benchmark @start postcond\n  let allSubseq := (nums.foldl fun acc x => acc ++ acc.map (fun sub => x :: sub)) [[]] |>.map List.reverse\n  let increasingSubseqLens := allSubseq.filter (fun l => List.Pairwise (· < ·) l) |>.map (·.length)\n  increasingSubseqLens.contains result ∧ increasingSubseqLens.all (· ≤ result)\n  -- !benchmark @end postcond\n\n\n-- !benchmark @start proof_aux\n\n-- !benchmark @end proof_aux\n\n\ntheorem longestIncreasingSubsequence_spec_satisfied (nums: List Int) (h_precond : longestIncreasingSubsequence_precond (nums)) :\n    longestIncreasingSubsequence_postcond (nums) (longestIncreasingSubsequence (nums) h_precond) h_precond := by\n  -- !benchmark @start proof\n  sorry\n```\n\nWe need to replace the `sorry` with a valid proof. Let's think about how to construct this proof.\n\nFirst, we need to understand what the function `longestIncreasingSubsequence` computes. It computes the length of the longest increasing subsequence in `nums`.\n\nThe definition of `longestIncreasingSubsequence` uses a recursive approach:\n- `max2 a b` returns the maximum of `a` and `b`.\n- `listLength l` returns the length of the list `l`.\n- `helper lst prev` computes the length of the longest increasing subsequence ending at the head of `lst` with `prev` as the previous element. If `prev` is `none`, then `canTake` is `true` (meaning we can take the first element). Otherwise, `canTake` is `true` if `prev < h` (the head of the current list segment `t`).\n- `withTake` is `1 + helper t (some h)` if `canTake` is `true`, otherwise `0`.\n- `withoutTake` is `helper t prev`.\n- `result` is `helper nums none`.\n\nThis is a standard dynamic programming approach for the longest increasing subsequence problem.\n\nNow, for the proof:\n- We need to show that `result` (the computed length) is in the set `increasingSubseqLens` and is the maximum element of this set.\n\nTo show `result ∈ increasingSubseqLens`:\n- We need to show that `result` is the length of some increasing subsequence.\n- Th